		</span>
	</div>

	<div class="commentcontent">
		<p>Some of this seems quite reductive, though. Aside from improving his golf game, what reasonable reason would Tiger Woods have to doubt his preeminence? If you're good at something, part of this is a rational evaluation of why and how you're good: in this case, excess doubt for doubt's sake is less an openended intellectual inquiry or humility than needless worrying, no doubt occasioned by some other unresolved issue.</p>

<p>Doubt seems like a useful heuristic for self-evaluation and for further learning: but I've yet to see a talented person who overindulges in doubts about their competence, skills, etc. work either very happily or well. A reasonable and hard-earned confidence is a gift to oneself, and to others: it allows us to be productive and joyous, two not-bad things in this difficult world.</p>
	</div>
</div>


        
    
        
